In an era in which climate change and SLR pose unprecedented threats to the coastal environment, urbanization, and population, Earth observation data, such as those provided by the European Space Agency Copernicus Sentinel-1A and Sentinel-1B satellites (launched on 3 April 2014 and 25 April 2016, respectively) and by the NISAR (NASA-ISRO SAR) satellite (the United States and India joint mission due to launch by 2021), will continue to provide crucial data to inform policy decisions (
 
  31
 ). These data can be used to improve flood resilience plans for coastal megacities around the world, most of which are located in river deltas and lowlands subject to subsidence and with significant populations exposed to flood risk (
 
  32
 ).
